items.title: Cassytha melantha
items.content_text: Black sepals are a key feature of this species (hence the name melantha). Pic 3 has a small insect on it, possibly a Hemiptera.

items.title: Correa backhouseana var. backhouseana
items.content_text: This 100m of coastline contains possibly the only extant population of this species on mainland Australia.

items.title: Notogrammitis billardierei
items.content_text: Two plants photographed, one on a tree and one on a log.

items.title: Comesperma ericinum
items.content_text: Really unusual form in this swamp. Only two records locally, 20km either side of this one, and both from about 1890. ID by NW.

items.title: Leptospermum continentale
items.content_text: Verging on L. scoparium on some plants (eg. pic1) but leaves broadest at base and tapering to tip as per L. continentale (see especially pic2). Unusual forms of many species in this swamp.

items.title: Epacris impressa var. impressa, Gleichenia dicarpa
Boronia parviflora
items.content_text: Pale pink and white flowered plants. Large sepals are a key feature.

items.title: Thelionema umbellatum
items.content_text: Nearest records are at Anglesea and Portland. New record for Great Otway NP.

items.title: Leucopogon parviflorus
items.content_text: An unusual inland swamp form of L. parviflorus.

items.title: Lepidosperma filiforme
items.content_text: Leaf and stem similar and terete.

items.title: Stylidium graminifolium s.s.
items.content_text: Leaves were quite wide at maybe 3.1mm wide.

items.title: Hakea ulicina
items.content_text: Leaf width would suggest H. repullulans but the signs of vegetative new growth on the second pic means it can only be H. ulicina.
